         <abstract>
            <p>In an article in the last issue of this Journal, entitled "Random Walks: Reality or Myth," Levy concluded that technical analysis can be useful in forecasting market price movements; that stock prices follow trends and patterns which have predictive significance; and that the theory of random walks thereby has been refuted. Professor Jensen, in the same issue, objected to Levy's findings, and contended one cannot be certain that his results did not arise from chance alone. Moreover, Levy's models were not independent but related observations and offered no underlying economic rationale. According to him, Levy had not refuted the random walk theory. Levy now proceeds to defend his original conclusions.</p>
          </abstract>
